  - number sense
  - DreamerV3
  - representation learning
  - representational geometry
  - Hamming distance
  - integration architecture
  - critical periods
  - VICReg
  - cooperative plasticity
abstract: >-
  Same concept, different physics, different geometry. A DreamerV3
  world model trained on grid-based counting develops a smooth 1D
  manifold (GHE=0.33). The same architecture trained on binary
  cascading counting develops a Hamming hypercube (GHE=4.91). The
  FP Unifier architecture integrates both geometric structures through
  frozen specialists, learned adapters, and a shared GRU integrator.
  Key findings: information and geometry are separable (per-bit
  accuracy stays 100% while geometric structure reorganizes completely),
  late regularization on a consolidated substrate outperforms early
  application (contradicting the critical periods framework), and
  integration requires cooperative residual plasticity between
  adapter and recurrent components.
